---
import SchemaLayout from '../../../layouts/SchemaLayout.astro';
import drugsData from '../../../../data/drugs.json';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;

const renalCount = drugsData.filter((d: any) => d.renal_dose_adjustment).length;
const hepaticCount = drugsData.filter((d: any) => d.hepatic_dose_adjustment).length;
const beersCount = drugsData.filter((d: any) => d.beers_criteria).length;
const cyp3a4Count = drugsData.filter((d: any) =>
  d.pharmacokinetics?.metabolism?.toLowerCase().includes('cyp3a4')
).length;
const tdmCount = drugsData.filter((d: any) => d.tdm_required).length;

const subPages = [
  {
    href: `${base}schemas/06-adme/absorption/`,
    title: 'Absorption',
    description: 'Bioavailability, first-pass effect, routes of administration, and factors affecting drug absorption.',
    icon: '💊',
    color: 'border-amber-400',
  },
  {
    href: `${base}schemas/06-adme/distribution/`,
    title: 'Distribution',
    description: 'Volume of distribution, protein binding, BBB penetration, and placental transfer.',
    icon: '🔬',
    color: 'border-amber-500',
  },
  {
    href: `${base}schemas/06-adme/cyp-metabolism/`,
    title: 'CYP Metabolism',
    description: 'CYP450 isoforms, inducers and inhibitors, prodrug activation, and genetic polymorphisms.',
    icon: '⚗️',
    color: 'border-amber-600',
  },
  {
    href: `${base}schemas/06-adme/excretion/`,
    title: 'Excretion',
    description: 'Renal clearance, dose adjustment in CKD, biliary excretion, and dialyzability.',
    icon: '🫘',
    color: 'border-amber-700',
  },
  {
    href: `${base}schemas/06-adme/special-populations/`,
    title: 'Special Populations',
    description: 'Pediatrics, geriatrics, pregnancy, lactation, and obesity considerations.',
    icon: '👥',
    color: 'border-amber-800',
  },
  {
    href: `${base}schemas/06-adme/drug-interactions-pk/`,
    title: 'PK Drug Interactions',
    description: 'Pharmacokinetic interactions, clinical significance grading, and management strategies.',
    icon: '⚠️',
    color: 'border-amber-900',
  },
];
---
<SchemaLayout
  title="ADME — Pharmacokinetic Schema"
  schema="adme"
  description="Explore drugs organized by absorption, distribution, metabolism, and excretion properties."
>
  <div class="mb-6">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-serif font-bold mb-2">Schema 6: ADME</h1>
    <p class="text-base-content/70 text-lg">Absorption · Distribution · Metabolism · Excretion</p>
  </div>

  <div class="prose max-w-none mb-10">
    <p>
      Pharmacokinetics — the study of what the body does to a drug — is encapsulated in the ADME
      framework: absorption, distribution, metabolism, and excretion. Understanding ADME is not
      merely an academic exercise; it is the mechanistic foundation upon which safe and effective
      drug therapy depends. A clinician who understands why oral metformin has near-complete
      bioavailability without first-pass metabolism, while oral nitroglycerin is almost entirely
      destroyed before reaching systemic circulation, can predict clinical outcomes, anticipate
      dose adjustments, and prevent life-threatening errors in ways that rote memorization cannot
      support. ADME principles explain why two drugs with identical mechanisms of action can have
      vastly different dosing schedules, why renal impairment transforms a standard dose into an
      overdose for renally-cleared drugs, and why a seemingly innocuous dietary change — drinking
      grapefruit juice — can convert a therapeutic dose of certain statins or calcineurin inhibitors
      into a toxic one.
    </p>
    <p>
      The ADME framework organizes pharmacokinetic knowledge along the drug's temporal journey
      through the body. Absorption governs the rate and extent to which a drug reaches the systemic
      circulation, shaped by molecular properties (lipophilicity, molecular weight, ionization state),
      formulation characteristics, and physiological variables from gastric pH to intestinal motility.
      Distribution describes the drug's subsequent partitioning into tissues, governed by plasma
      protein binding, lipophilicity, and tissue-specific transporters — processes that determine
      whether a drug reaches its target organ at therapeutically relevant concentrations and whether
      it penetrates protected compartments such as the central nervous system, the placenta, or
      abscess cavities. Metabolism, principally hepatic but also occurring in the gut wall, lung,
      and kidney, chemically transforms drugs through oxidation, conjugation, and hydrolysis — a
      process mediated largely by the cytochrome P450 enzyme family whose genetic variability and
      susceptibility to induction and inhibition underlies the majority of clinically significant
      drug interactions. Excretion describes the elimination of drug and metabolites from the body,
      predominantly through renal filtration, secretion, and reabsorption, with biliary and pulmonary
      routes contributing for specific drug classes.
    </p>
    <p>
      For the nursing clinician, ADME mastery translates directly into patient safety practices:
      recognizing which patients require dose adjustments based on organ function, understanding
      why crushing an extended-release tablet can produce fatal drug concentrations, anticipating
      the delay between administration and therapeutic effect for drugs with long distribution phases,
      and counseling patients about food and drug interactions with mechanistic specificity rather
      than a list of prohibitions. The {drugsData.length} drugs indexed in this reference span an
      enormous range of pharmacokinetic profiles — from vancomycin, renally cleared unchanged with
      dose adjustment required in {renalCount} drugs of this database, to highly lipophilic agents
      with volumes of distribution exceeding total body water. {cyp3a4Count} drugs in this database
      are metabolized by CYP3A4, the single most important drug-metabolizing enzyme; {hepaticCount}
      require hepatic dose adjustment; and {beersCount} appear on the Beers Criteria for potentially
      inappropriate use in older adults whose pharmacokinetic capacity is diminished. Navigate the
      six sub-sections below to explore each dimension of ADME in full clinical and mechanistic
      depth.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- Stats bar -->
  <div class="stats stats-horizontal shadow w-full mb-10 flex-wrap">
    <div class="stat">
      <div class="stat-title">CYP3A4 Substrates</div>
      <div class="stat-value text-amber-600">{cyp3a4Count}</div>
      <div class="stat-desc">drugs in database</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat">
      <div class="stat-title">Renal Dose Adj.</div>
      <div class="stat-value text-amber-600">{renalCount}</div>
      <div class="stat-desc">require CKD adjustment</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat">
      <div class="stat-title">Hepatic Dose Adj.</div>
      <div class="stat-value text-amber-600">{hepaticCount}</div>
      <div class="stat-desc">require liver adjustment</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat">
      <div class="stat-title">Beers Criteria</div>
      <div class="stat-value text-amber-600">{beersCount}</div>
      <div class="stat-desc">avoid in elderly</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat">
      <div class="stat-title">TDM Required</div>
      <div class="stat-value text-amber-600">{tdmCount}</div>
      <div class="stat-desc">therapeutic drug monitoring</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Sub-page card grid -->
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif font-bold mb-4">Explore ADME Sub-Sections</h2>
  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6 mb-10">
    {subPages.map((page) => (
      <a href={page.href} class={`card card-compact bg-base-100 shadow-md border-l-4 ${page.color} hover:shadow-lg transition-shadow`}>
        <div class="card-body">
          <div class="text-3xl mb-2">{page.icon}</div>
          <h3 class="card-title font-serif">{page.title}</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-base-content/70">{page.description}</p>
        </div>
      </a>
    ))}
  </div>

  <div class="alert alert-info">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" class="stroke-current shrink-0 w-6 h-6"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 16h-1v-4h-1m1-4h.01M21 12a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"></path></svg>
    <div>
      <div class="font-bold">Cross-Schema Navigation</div>
      <div class="text-sm">
        ADME properties link directly to drug interactions (Schema 9), adverse effect clusters (Schema 8),
        and special-population safety profiles. Use the Schema Compass to navigate between schemas for any drug.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</SchemaLayout>
